posts.com: Is there a good video that teaches me how to sample? I don't know how to make stuff on my own but I've heard sampling is a good way to learn how to make songs

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114841723
Learning to sample is alot of just doing it. There is not one way of sampling, there isnt some trick to learning what to listen for. Everything can be a sample given the right context. I've sampled everything from classical, jazz, hip hop, edm, film scores and death metal and grindcore.

I guess the only thing I can tell you about sampling is learning how to tempo match and figuring out the key of whatever you're sampling. You're also going to get very familiar with the limits of digital sound and aliasing so getting the highest available bitrate of whatever track you're sampling is also important.

>>114841134
Because sometimes you'll want to put certain effects / processing on one instrument and not others. Or you'll want to edit the patterns for a single instrument and leave the others alone. Also when you do more advanced compositions you'll sometimes have different instruments playing in the same range (though I don't recommend this unless you really know wtf you're doing) and keeping everything in one midi track will get confusing fast.

In orchestration there's a reason each instrument has its own staff on the sheet music, if every single performer were to play off the grand staff shit would be a clusterfuck.

But the market is driven by people like this... companies would go bankrupt without consumers like these... Best tones from classic albums were achieved using some sort improvised gear or some audio engineer found some black box gathering dust "hey lets try this out", you can never really replace knowledge with gear.

Does anyone here use a MIDI keyboard for synth playing or use midi pads to play drums? I will need a midi keyboard for my demo and I have previously decided on the Nektar T4 (I decided to buy, didn't buy though). I like:
>supposedly best keybed of all cheaper midi controllers
>"good" pads (whatever that means)
>infinitely spinning knobs
>has sliders
>supposedly good aftertouch
The Nektar LX+ is the same thing, but with finite knobs. I don't like the idea of soft takeover, so I am willing to literally double the price to get the T4.
T4: $250
LX+: $125.
Metal synth playing, like Synthphonia Suprema:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UkjOhWuwVFo

I also want to fuck about (yes, fuck about!) trying to tap out drum solos like these:
https://youtu.be/C7WZhJsIO9g?t=333
Both the Nektar T4 and LX+ only have 8 drum pads. I know it's stupid to try to tap out metal drums, but I think that tapping out drum solo (as opposed to drum beats) has merit for developing inspiration. Tapping out beats is not my interest, I can just program those. I want to tap out solos and have fun doing this.

I was originally (months ago) planning on buying an Akai MPK2whatever, but I felt one up in a guitar center, and the buttons felt unbelievably cheap. The kicker: Someone online said the aftertouch was difficult to control. The Akai is $450. Why spend that much if it's not the best?

I want all the bells and whistles, and I want them all to be SOLID.
>aftertouch
>keybed
>sliders
>knobs (infinite)
>PADS
>pitch wheel

Of course, I am a degree of idiot, and it's better to have something (to create with) instead of nothing; But I also live by the adage: The poor man pays twice. (I will not buy a sub-bar product then buy a bar product later). Thus now, I have paid naught, AND I HAVE NAUGHT. I need something, and unless I find the perfect MIDI controller soon, I'm just going to pop 4 the Nek' T4, yeah?

I'm thinking 49 keys.

- I am a bird
Ahhhh!

Here's something I have noticed - Peter Gabriel's solo music seems darker if you assume that Phil Collins raped him. I'm not saying it happened. I'm just asking questions. I'd just say that there is nothing inconsistent with this possibility within his discography. There are no PG songs which make me think "this is not the sort of song that a man raped by Phil Collins would write."

In fact, if you look at his 1980 single "No Self Control," one could easily imagine the song being sung by PG from the perspective of the rapist Collins, while the b-side "Lead a Normal Life" is from the victim's perspective.

And of course, songs like 'Intruder' make perfect sense in this context. It's just so obvious. Digging in the Dirt, Don't Give Up, No Way Out, Shock the Monkey, Games Without Frontiers, I Have the Touch, etc. He's never really gotten over the rape by Phil.

Or consider a song like "Not One of Us." It is equal parts anger towards the rapist Collins mixed with self-doubt caused by the assault. Collins' violent act makes him an animal, ie, not part of humanity. Yet, the victim no longer feels human either, due to his shame.

Consider the following:

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3yEcTB2va5E

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-GgEu0Sbiv8

Frankly, you could also look at PHIL'S solo work as evidence of a man who knows what he did, but who refuses to take responsibility. 'This Must Be Love'? 'I Don't Care Anymore'? 'Both Sides of the Story'? 'Two Hearts'? 'Don't Lose My Number'? 'One More Night'? 'Why Can't It Wait 'Til Morning'? 'It Don't Matter to Me'? 'Easy Lover'? (LOL).

Good God, /mu/. We've cracked the case.

posts.sub: /MTASGG/ Music That Actually Sounds Good General
posts.com:
This General is for the discussion of music that actually sounds good, which people enjoy because they genuinely take pleasure in the sonic listening experience, rather than for any kind of contrived reason.

Examples of genuine reasons for appreciating music:
>melody
>hooks
>riffs
>rhythm
>beat
>bassline
>textures
>energy
>emotion

Examples of disingenuous, contrived and pretentious reasons for appreciating music:
>the artistic or intellectual concepts and themes behind the music rather than the actual music itself
>the technical ability of the musician
>the meaning of the lyrics
>the degree of “experimentation”
>the prog qualities of the music such as odd timings or complicated sequences done purely for the sake of being prog and not because they serve the song itself
>the song being related to an adjacent subculture such as gaming or Japanese weeaboo fandom

There is a pandemic of autism on this board which causes many users here to fundamentally misunderstand what the primary purpose of music actually is: Sounding pleasant to the ear.

Post songs that you like because they sound good and for no other reason.

posts.com:
Another incredible band is The Birthday Massacre. They've gone on DECADES without any drop in quality, and despite the fact that every TBM song sounds like a TBM song, they've managed to stay fresh and keep cranking out absolute bangers.
It's impossible to appreciate them fully without listening to the albums all the way through, looking at the disc artwork, and just zoning out and letting your imagination run wild. Every album has sort of a theme and listening to them all the way through feels like you're being told a story. Superstition in particular is about death and the other side, and I get absolute CHILLS when they play Trinity at the very end.
They've had a bunch of purely melodic/atmospheric tracks like that ever since Violet, but usually they're transitional interludes between songs. Ending an album on one is ballsy and used to great effect.
They're also really great performers live. They actually dance and sing and have a fun time with the crowd. I've seen Chibi just dance with a kid from the crowd onstage before.
And her voice? Chibi's voice is absolutely haunting. It sounds childlike, yeah, but that's what makes it so eerie and piercing to hear her sing. It fits the theme of the band perfectly. It's innocent and childlike and magical and imaginative but also haunting and creepy and jarring and dark.
The lyrics are insane. They're like actually-good goth poetry and some of the darkest shit I've ever heard in terms of content, but the sound itself is so sparkly and radiant and energetic that you wouldn't hear how soul-crushingly sad it can get when you actually listen to the words.
And the words? Holy moly, I love it when they repeat lyrics in different tracks across DECADES. It gave me goosebumps to hear "You watch me as I fall" in Diamonds after they used the same line in Enter AND Shiver.

Imma throw this out there since OP seems genuinely responsive.
The Spyro the Dragon soundtrack by Stewart Copeland of The Police is legitimately good.
Yes, it's an OST and it's nostalgiabait. But somehow Copeland managed to base an ENTIRE soundtrack off of a single song. The leitmotif, the banjo interlude, the chimes, and the drum tracks get repeated CONSTANTLY and that's a good thing, because in your first playthrough you won't even notice that it's ALL the same song.
The final boss theme has the guitar "RRROOOWW" that the game boots up on when you first put in the disc. Perfect bookends. I love it and it disappoints me that 2 and 3 didn't keep the pattern of literally just all being the title screen theme.

I get that the violin is a complicated and beautiful instrument, but as a complete pleb and shitlord, there's so goddamn much of it to me so many songs sound the same, either some "bright" or "sad" violin crap for 7 minutes followed by applause.

I'd just like to point out that my mom saw Rachmaninoff play when she was in high school and, while that only means that I'm an old fart, the mildly entertaining aspect of this is the reactions she got from her co-workers and peers in the '70s and '80s.

Mom was born in 1921 and her parents took her see him playing with the Cleveland Symphony sometime in the late '30s. When we moved to San Francisco in the early '70s (I was in high school then), we fell in with a group of younger coworkers at mom's law firm who were classical fans and we went to the winter Symphony concerts with them once in awhile. One show featured Piano Concerto #2, damned if I can recall who the soloist was. Anyway, mom mentioned in passing that she had seen him perform this very piece back when and her coworkers were simply stunned. So mom chided them a little about it and went with, "all that means is that I'm old". She was in her early '50s then, so clearly "not all that old" at all.

Thanks for following my blog don't forget to hit like and subscribe.

Kendrick's not a great musician, he's just a great lyricist. GKMC was very solid, but it was a basic bitch album. There's a reason why every kid was bumping it for months when it first came out, it's basically a J Cole album, but good. TPAB had deeper subject matter and great lyricism within certain songs but the overarching concept of the album was overwrought and the Tupac interview was extreme cringe. It's also way too long and has some really boring songs in the second half. TPAB is his only album where the instrumentation excels beyond hip hop conventions, but Kendrick had nothing to do with any of it. It was going to be a typical boom bap record before he linked up with Thundercat, who introduced him to Miles Davis and other jazz legends.

They then brought a bunch of musicians into the studio to freestyle and Kendrick just rapped over it. Once you're aware of this you can clearly hear which songs on the album were produced before Kendrick was introduced to jazz (the standard boom bap songs) and which ones were added in later in the process. Kendrick doesn't possess any of the musical knowledge or vision that someone like Kanye does, he just raps.

This is why DAMN and MMBS was back to being a basic hip hop record, cause he didn't bring the jazz musicians back to the studio. DAMN and MMBS are also forgettable, it's pretty common for lyrical rappers to run out of things to say after a couple of records and that seems to be what happened to Kendrick. All in all, he's a great rapper, but the only reason he achieved a greater reputation than someone like Mos Def or Lupe Fiasco is because A.) He had better production on his first two albums, and B.) The political climate of the mid-2010s during the rise of BLM conveniently made Kendrick the most "important" contemporary artist in their eyes.

It's usually so much better than stuff that's been watered down by social graces. I kind of think the same way about music theory. I know that the idea of theory as a prescriptive rulebook is a stupid meme and not true but at the same time, if you're learning how to do something creative through the lens and opinions of other people/the masses, how can you prevent that from tainting your own art? If the base you're building from is made up of old ideas from long dead nobodies then you aren't really developing a personal style as much as you could be, you're essentially just becoming a different flavor of traditional music. Which isn't bad, there's a lot of traditional and theory based music that is good just none that blows me away like the stuff made by weirdos. If your goal is commercially successful music then you basically have to learn theory and you're either an idiot or a savant if you don't. But if you want to make interesting music, you shouldn't just learn to colour outside the lines, you should erase the lines entirely.

Technology has not made gear obsolete when it comes to circuits/pedals/preamps, only made them even more relevant and breathed new life into them.

Hohner are reliable if you just want a basic diatonic, Suzukis are probably my favourite. Seydels are great but might be a bit pricey if you are just dipping your toes in. Easttop used to be really good value in return for shit quality control (because Chinafactorylol) but then too many influencers made videos about "the secretly great cheap harmonicas from China" and now they are almost as expensive as western harps but still with shit quality control (a good one does have a lovely tone though). If you are just starting out with harmonica you can't go wrong with a Hohner Marine Band in C, E, A or G, if that is out of your budget then opt for a Hohner International or Easttop 008K Blues Harmonica, start with that and then if you feel you have "outgrown" it then start looking into what parts of a sound (breathiness, bend availability, tone) you want to chase and buy accordingly.
If your heart is set on trying a chromatic then Johnson sell a cheap and cheerful chromatic 24 hole that can at least get you familiar with the playstyle. Hope this helps anon.

>>114855468
I play some instruments left handed (guitar, bass, wind instruments that allow for either handing) some instruments right handed (lap steel, wind instruments that don't allow it) and some in a split style (drums I play left handed but the kit is set up right handed since that is what I learned on being the main one). Left handers don't necessarily need to play guitar left handed, but some left handed players will severely hinder their development if they learn conventional. The comparison I like to draw is to ask right handers to TRY and play leftie for a few weeks. They will generally find that they can learn chord shapes VERY easily, their fretting hand development is incredibly quick... And then they can't do anything more than single string picking or basic strumming even after weeks and months of trying it.
Pick up a guitar, strum it a few times, try and pluck individual strings a few times, try to fret a few times, and establish which handedness you are most comfortable with. Don't care about what hand you write with or what hand you throw a ball with or anything, perform the motor functions on a guitar each way and see which one you find more comfortable and go with that. However, give preference to which hand is more comfortable to strum with. The hardest part of the first year of learning guitar is learning to navigate a fretboard and replicate positions, the rest of your life playing guitar is about nailing your rhythm. Don't force yourself to play the handedness someone tells you to, whether it be some guy complaining that we don't have to make special violins for southpaws or the person that definitely experienced a shoah in 90s schooling where a teacher beat them half to death for picking up a pencil in their left hand. These people will send you on their own crusades to the detriment of your own playing.
